performed_via_github_app.name: Netlify
performed_via_github_app.description:
Publish incredibly high performance websites and applications right from GitHub. The Netlify platform connects your repositories to an all-in-one workflow for global CDN deployment, continuous integration, and automatic (and free) HTTPS. Each time you commit changes, Netlify builds your site, prerenders markup, and optimizes assets on dedicated build infrastructure. Easily create an entirely automated workflow around any site generator such as Jekyll, Hugo, or Gatsby.

## Features

### Push your site live, directly from GitHub
Deploy your site to an ultra-redundant global CDN that’s purpose built for serving pages and assets quickly and consistently.

### Automate deployment
Netlify’s built-in Continuous Deployment automatically runs your build commands and deploys the result whenever you push to your Git repository.

### Add a custom domain
Purchase domains and manage DNS zones and records right inside of Netlify.

### HTTPS is automatic
Your site will automatically be secured with a free TLS certificate from Let’s Encrypt.

### Deploy Previews
Netlify’s Deploy Previews streamlined your workflow by giving you a unique, permanent URL to check what your changes will be like in production whenever you submit a pull request.

### And a lot more!
Netlify includes solutions for forms, identity, and even custom functions powered by AWS Lambda. And all this functionality can be configured directly in your repo.

review.body:
## Pull Request Overview

This PR implements an automated versioning and tagging system to support deployments. Key changes include adding version configuration to all environment files, updating the game view to display version information, and enhancing CI workflows with scripts for version replacement and tag creation.
- Updated environment files (development, production, GitHub Pages) with a versionConfig object.
- Added a script (version-config.js) to inject version details and updated package.json scripts accordingly.
- Updated CI workflows to prepare commit SHA, build with versioning, and create Git tags on successful deployments.

### Reviewed Changes

Copilot reviewed 12 out of 12 changed files in this pull request and generated 1 comment.

<details>
<summary>Show a summary per file</summary>

| File | Description |
| ---- | ----------- |
| src/environments/environment.ts | Added versionConfig with version placeholders. |
| src/environments/environment.prod.ts | Added versionConfig with version placeholders. |
| src/environments/environment.githubpages.ts | Added versionConfig with a different versionName configuration. |
| src/app/game/game.page.ts | Introduced versionConfig to expose version info from environment. |
| src/app/game/game.page.html | Displayed version information in the footer. |
| scripts/version-config.js | Script to replace version placeholders with package values and commit details. |
| package.json | Updated version and added prebuild and version:config scripts. |
| CI workflows (.github/workflows/*) | Updated workflows to include commit SHA preparation, build steps, and Git tagging. |
| .github/actions/prepare-sha/action.yml | Added action to set the commit SHA into the workflow environment. |
</details>



<details>
<summary>Comments suppressed due to low confidence (1)</summary>

**src/app/game/game.page.ts:35**
* [nitpick] Consider adding a semicolon at the end of the debugMode property assignment for consistency with other code style conventions in the file.
```
   debugMode = false
```
</details>

milestone.title: v0.5.0
milestone.description:
Users should be able to use `turbopelican.toml` to configure their project fully, not just for the present subset of settings that are handled. This configuration can be found from https://docs.getpelican.com/en/latest/settings.html. Also, Turbopelican, when loading configuration, should use a priority ranking for settings in this order:

1. Is the setting set explicitly?
2. If not, is the setting set in an inherited section? (Only applicable to publishconf.py)
3. If not, is there a default setting?

If the answer to all these is no for any given setting, Turbopelican should raise an error.

Fix AlmaLinux CI: handle curl-minimal conflict

This fixes the AlmaLinux test failures in CI.
